-- Cocoa Has Biggest Two-Day Gain in 11 Years: Commodities at Close
-- B y   P a u l   B u r k h a r d t
-- 2012-01-10T21:46:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-10/cocoa-has-biggest-two-day-gain-in-11-years-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI Spot
 Index (SPGSCI)  of 24 commodities rose 0.9 percent to close at 668.43 at
3:48 p.m. in  New York , led by cocoa.  The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials rose 1
percent to 1,566.485.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures fell to the lowest price in more than
two years in New York on speculation that stockpiles declined
last week at below-normal rates, widening a surplus of the fuel
over the five-year average.  Natural gas for February delivery fell 7 cents, or 2.3
percent to $2.941 per million British thermal units on the New
York Mercantile Exchange, the lowest settlement price since
Sept. 9, 2009. The futures have declined 33 percent from a year
earlier.  U.K. summer natural gas slumped, reversing gains, as mild
weather curbed demand for the heating fuel and supplies were
ample.  Summer gas, for delivery in the six months from April, fell
as much as 0.6 pence to 53.45 pence a therm. It was at 54.45
pence at 4:30 p.m. That’s equal to $8.28 a million British
thermal units.  BASE METALS  Copper posted the biggest gain in almost six weeks as
imports climbed to a record in  China , the world’s biggest user
of industrial metals.  Copper futures for March delivery advanced 2.8 percent to
settle at $3.513 a pound at 1:16 p.m. on the Comex in New York,
the biggest gain for a most-active contract since Nov. 30.  On the London Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months rose 3.3 percent to $7,740 a metric ton ($3.51 a pound).  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cocoa futures jumped, capping the biggest two-day gain in
almost 11 years, after a nationwide strike spurred concerns that
supplies will be disrupted in  Nigeria , the world’s fourth-
largest producer.  Cocoa for March delivery rose 7.5 percent to close at
$2,333 a metric ton at 12:04 p.m. on ICE Futures U.S. in New
York. In two days, the price soared 15 percent, the most since
Jan. 17, 2001.  Raw-sugar futures for March delivery fell 0.1 percent to
23.32 cents a pound.  March-delivery Arabica-coffee futures rose 1.8 percent to
$2.2595 a pound, the biggest gain since Dec. 19.  Cotton futures for March delivery advanced 0.5 percent to
96.96 cents a pound.  Orange-juice  futures rose the most in five years as
freezing weather damages citrus crops in  Florida , and a U.S.
government probe of a fungicide used on fruit in  Brazil  may
limit imports.  Orange juice for March delivery jumped the 20-cent exchange
limit, or 11 percent, to settle at $2.0775 a pound at 2 p.m. on
ICE Futures U.S. in New York, a record for the contract and the
highest level for a most-active contract since March 2007.  CRUDE OIL  Oil rose for the first time in four days on renewed concern
that Middle East tension will disrupt supply and as equities
advanced, increasing economic optimism.  Crude for February delivery climbed 93 cents, or 0.9
percent, to settle at $102.24 a barrel on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange . West Texas Intermediate oil traded on the
Nymex has surged 20 percent in the past three months.  Brent oil for February settlement increased 83 cents, or
0.7 percent, to $113.28 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures
Europe exchange.  Royal Dutch Plc sold two more cargoes of North Sea Forties
crude, bringing its total sales for January loading shipments to
11. Gunvor Group Ltd. bought Russian Urals in northwest Europe
at a higher price.  U.S. Gulf Coast oils weakened after refineries in Texas and
 Louisiana  shut process units for planned work, reducing demand
for crude.  The spot price of Dubai crude, the benchmark grade for
Middle East oil, fell for the first time in three days, trimming
its weekly gain.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline rose a third consecutive day on Iran political
tension and on concern refinery shutdowns in  Europe  and the U.S.
will reduce fuel supplies.  Gasoline for February delivery gained 1.38 cents, or 0.5
percent, to settle at $2.7728 a gallon on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.  February-delivery heating oil rose 2.84 cents, or 0.9
percent, to $3.1014 a gallon on the exchange, the third
consecutive increase.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold futures closed at the highest price in four weeks as a
weaker dollar bolstered demand for commodities. Silver, platinum
and palladium also surged.  Gold futures for February delivery advanced 1.5 percent to
settle at $1,631.50 an ounce at 1:48 p.m. on the Comex in New
York, the highest closing price since Dec. 13. The precious
metal rose as high as $1,61.40, the highest level since Dec. 21.  Silver futures for March delivery climbed 3.6 percent to
$29.815 an ounce on the Comex. Earlier, the price reached
$30.31, the highest since Dec. 14.  Platinum futures for April delivery rose 2.4 percent to
$1,464.60 an ounce on the New York Mercantile Exchange.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Wheat futures fell for the fourth time in five sessions on
speculation that U.S. supplies will be ample as precipitation
eases a drought in the Great Plains, where farmers have boosted
planting.  Wheat futures for March delivery sank 0.3 percent to settle
at $6.3975 a bushel at 1:15 p.m. on the Chicago Board of Trade.  Soybean futures for March delivery dropped 0.1 percent to
close at $12.32 a bushel at 1:15 p.m. on the Chicago Board of
Trade. Earlier, the price fell as much as 1 percent. The
commodity has declined 11 percent in the past 12 months.  LIVESTOCK  Hog futures climbed the most in a week on speculation that
demand for U.S. pork is increasing. Cattle prices rose, marking
the first gain in four sessions.  Hog futures for February settlement advanced 1.1 percent to
settle at 84.3 cents a pound at 1 p.m. on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, the biggest gain for the most-active contract since
Jan. 3. The price has added 5.8 percent in the past 12 months.  Cattle futures for February delivery climbed 1 percent to
settle at $1.212 a pound on the CME.  To contact the reporter on this story:
